summary: 365 Marvel Villain paper cut-outs - one villain, every day, all year. March 4th - Deathbird The eldest daughter of the ruling...
caption:
365 Marvel Villain paper cut-outs - one villain, every day, all year.

March 4th - Deathbird

The eldest daughter of the ruling house of the Shi'Ar Imperium.  An interpretation of a prophecy within this alien empire suggested that Deathbird would commit a terrible crime and for this she was banished.  She was somehow able to travel to earth where she became involved with the organization of science terrorists known as A.I.M.  Deathbird battled Ms. Marvel to prevent her from unearthing AIM’s schemes.  Ms. Marvel prevailed and Deathbird was forced into hiding.  She later reappeared to battle Hawkeye. After Deathbird’s younger sister ascended to the throne of the Shi’Ar Imperium, Deathbird led a group of dissidents in an effort to dethrone her; a plot that was ultimately foiled by the X-Men.  Some time thereafter, she aided The X-Men in a battle against The Phalanx.  Following this adventure Deathbird had a brief romance with The X-man known as Bishop.  Her first appearance was in Ms. marvel Vol. 1 #9

summary: “With the adrenaline subsiding, I’m feeling something much more troubling: anxiety, mixed with a hefty dose of doubt as to what...
body:
“With the adrenaline subsiding, I’m feeling something much more troubling: anxiety, mixed with a hefty dose of doubt as to what it is we’re about to do here, and whether I can do it at all.

I sift through some of my emotions, trying to land on something to share that will ease this burden but that won’t completely scare Maria off. I haven’t had that many opportunities to have a best friend—certainly not someone as awesome as her. I don’t want to alarm her with the part of brain that’s suddenly speeding ahead faster than the Mustang, cycling through everything that could go wrong and every way that we could fail and prove our naysayers right.”

— Carol Danvers in Higher, Further, Faster by Liza Palmer
